[EEE infection is reported rarely in dogs (canines), and cases most commonly occur in puppies. Although early signs typically consist of fever and gastrointestinal upset, severe neurologic signs usually develop 1-2 days later. Prior to the neurological signs developing, one would have to rule out parvovirus infection. Once neurological signs appear, then rabies might be high on the differential list. While gross anatomic lesions are rare in infected dogs, humans, primates, and horses, histopathology can include neuronal necrosis, hemorrhage, vasculitis, edema, and encephalitis.
(Portions extracted from https://www.americanveterinarian.com/news/eastern-equine-encephalitis-rare-but-serious-in-dogs) - Mod.TG

EEE virus has been identified as the cause of death in young domestic dogs. It was responsible for the deaths of 3 puppies in Michigan and New York and in 12 dogs of less than 6 months of age in Georgia. However, no mention is made about presence of and titers of viremias in these dogs, so one does not know if they were able to provide infectious blood meals fo mosquitoes while still alive that would facilitate ongoing transmission of the virus. - Mod. TY

